@AFFECTS

&2Affects&n

&3Usage:&n &4affects&n

An affect is something that modifies your attributes.
These are usually made active on you by casting spells or using skills.

This command displays all of your current affects, at level 20 the
amount of information displayed is increased.
#
ALIAS ALIASES

&2Alias or Aliases&n

&3Usage:&n &4alias [<alias name>] [command]&n

An alias is a single command used to represent one or more other commands.
The &4ALIAS&n command can be used to manipulate your character's aliases.  Type
&4ALIAS&n alone to see a list of your currently defined aliases.
The &3<alias name>&n must be one word.  The &3command&n can be any string.  
Aliases may not be nested or used recursively.  Any command may be overridden 
by an alias (other than the &4ALIAS&n command itself, of course).

  > &4alias gbb get bread bag&n
  > &4alias gac get all corpse&n

Type &4alias <alias-name>&n to delete an alias that has already been defined.

  > &4alias gbb&n

A semicolon (";") can be used to define multiple actions to be taken with
a single alias. 
(Note a semicolon may be interpreted differently as "input" in some clients)

  > &4alias eat get bread bag; eat bread&n

Note that the 'eat' contained within the eat alias is interpreted as the MUD's
internal eat command; aliases may not be nested or used recursively.  The
variables &3$1, $2, ... $9&n may be used to represent arguments given with
an alias.

Examples:

  > &4alias killem cast 'fireball' $1; cast 'harm' $2&n
  > &4killem fido mage&n

Would cast fireball on fido, followed by casting harm on mage.  Variables
may be used repeatedly and in any order:

  > &4alias helpem cast 'heal' $1; cast 'bless' $1; cast 'armor' $1&n

The special variable &3$*&n represents the entire input line after an alias:

  > &4alias tr tell rasmussen $*&n
  > &4tr hi there, how are you today?&n
  &rYou tell &7Rasmussen&r, 'hi there, how are you today?'&n

See also: &3! ^&n
#
ANSI COLOUR COLOR
&2"Ansi Colour"&n

&3Usage:&n &4colour [off | sparse | normal | complete]&n

If you have a colour-capable terminal and wish to see useful colour-coding
of information, use the &4colour&n command to set the level of colouring you see.
These four subcommands turn colour on && off to various levels.  Experiment to see
which level suits your personal taste.

'&4colour&n' with no argument will display your current colour level.

Using colour will slow down the speed at which you see messages VERY slightly.
The effect is more noticeable on slower connections.  Even if you have
colour turned on, non-colourised messages will not be slowed down at all.

&RPrimalMUD&n implements &rEasy Colour v2.2&n, which interprets inline colour codes.
Colours can be displayed in your text by inserting a &3&&&n followed by a &3<char code>&n.

The &3<char codes>&n correspond to the following colours:
&rr	Red&n 		&gg	Green&n 	
&yy	Yellow&n		&bb	Blue&n
&mm	Magenta&n 	&cc	Cyan&n
&ww	White&n
&RR	Bold Red&n 	&GG	Bold Green&n
&YY	Bold Yellow&n 	&BB	Bold Blue&n
&MM	Bold Magenta&n 	&CC	Bold Cyan&n
&WW	Bold White&n

Additionally, there are a number of special codes including:
&nn	Normal&n	
&vv	Reverse&n	
&uu	Underline&n
[	Set mark&n	]	Colour of set mark&n

example:
  > &4gossip &&[I am feeling a bit &&GSICK&&] today!&n
            ^ 			       ^    	
          colour                   changes
	 here is  		  to colour
	  yellow  	      at last mark (&&[ = yellow)
              \/                      \/
  &yYou gossip, 'I am feeling a bit &[&GSICK&] today!'

See also: &3COLOURSET&n
#
AREAS

&2Areas&n

This command will bring up a listing of the current areas playable in 
the realm.  It will give you the zone name, zone level, zone type (being
pkill or not) and the Author.
#
ASSASSIN ASSASSINATE

&2Assassin  Assassinate&n

&3Usage:&n &4assassinate <player name>&n

When venturing around the game you may come across the Assassin sitting in
the Assassin's Guild. This character will let you hire him for the usage of
removing a player from the game. This will cost you money!  If you find you
are on the receiving end of the assassin you can always try to turn him around
onto the player that originally hired him.
#
"ASSIST"

&2"Assist"&n

&3Usage:&n &4assist <person in need>&n

If &7Quifael&n is being beaten senseless by a &6warg&n and you feel brave enough
to help him, the &2assist&n command can be used.  Note that the &6warg&n will keep 
hitting &7Quifael&n; &2assist&n only makes you start to fight whomever the person you're
assisting is fighting.

See also: &3FLEE, KILL, RESCUE&n
#
"AUCTION"

&2Auction"&n

&3Usage:&n &4auction <item wanting to be auctioned off> <starting price>&n

This is the command to start an auction on unwanted items you have found whilst
you are playing. If you type &4auction&n and return by itself it will show you
a listing of what &4auction&n commands are available. They are as follows:

&4auction stat <item #>&n

To obtain the item number use &4auction list&n to find the item you are interested
in and then use that number to stat the object being auctioned off.

&4auction <item#> <price>&n

This is the bidding command, to do this you must have enough gold to place the 
bid and obviously you must outbid everyone else. Please be aware that you must
have enough gold in the BANK to place your bids.

&4auction list&n

The command to find out who is auctioning what and the item number you are 
interested in.

&4auction cancel&n

This is for those who want to cancel auctions!

&4auction sold&n

This command will finalise the auction to the last bidder. It will automatically
transfer the item in your inventory to the player who won the auction and will
transfer the funds to you.

&4noauction&n

This toggles the auction channel off or on.
#
"AUTOCORPSE"

&2autocorpse&n

This command will toggle the corpse retrieval service on and off.  If you die 
during play and have autocorpse on you will find your corpse waiting for you in
the local tavern.  This is a very handy tool if you plan on dying a lot! But be
warned this is also an expensive tool. The exp you lose on death is around half
the exp you gained ini your level to a max of 1/4 of the level BUT autocorpse
will cost you an additional 50% of the exp you are about to lose!
#
AUTOASSIST

&2autoassist&n

&3Usage: &4autoasist <player>&n
 
To automatically assist another player, handy if you are following them, or 
grouped. To turn this feature off just type &4autoassist&n.

See also: &3ASSIST, AUTOGOLD, AUTOLOOT, AUTOSPLIT&n
#
AUTOEAT

&2Autoeat&n

&3Usage:&n &4autoeat&n

This command will enable or disable your character from eating when hungry.
Whether you have food in your hand or in your backpack you will automatically
eat when the "You are hungry" appears on your screen.
#
AUTOEXIT

&2Autoexit&n

&3Usage:&n &4autoexit&n

This command will enable or disable autoexits. When enabled, the room 
description will include a list of obvious exits. Be warned, the 
obvious exits are not always all the exits....
#
AUTOGOLD

&2autogold&n

&3Usage: &4autogold&n

This command will enable or disable the facility to automatically remove
all gold from the mob once you have killed it.

See Also: &3AUTOSPLIT, AUTOLOOT&n
#
AUTOLOOT

&2autoloot&n

&3Usage: &4autoloot&n

This command will enable or disable the facility to automatically remove
all objects from the mob once you have killed it.

See also: &3AUTOGOLD, AUTOSPLIT&n
#
AUTOSPLIT

&2autosplit&n

&3Usage: &4autosplit&n

This command will enable or disable the facility to automatically &3split&n
gold collected between group members. 

See also: &3SPLIT, AUTOGOLD, AUTOLOOT&n
#
BITE

&2Bite&n

&3Usage:&n &4bite <player name>&n

Bite is the command that you use when you want to infect another player
with the werewolf or vampire infections! The only limits to this is you
have to be infected yourself and you have to be asuming the infection at
the time!
#
BLAST

&2Blast&n

&3Usage:&n &4blast <mob>&n

Blast is a command that is similar to Hit or Kill. 

See also: &3HIT KILL&n
#
"BOUNTY"

&2bounty&n

&3Usage:&n &4bounty <playername> <reward>&n

When a player becomes annoying to one or all there is
this feature that can be used to reward those who want
to act as bounty hunters! This feature is able to be used
to let a player know that he has been intolerable within 
the game! Use it wisely and you do not want it turned around
upon you!
#
"BREAKIN"

&2breakin&n

&3Usage:&n &4breakin <victim>&n

Use this when you think you have found a mob that would be of assistance while
you play. Not all mobs are able to be broken in. To be able to mount the mob 
you must have the skill mount practiced.

See also: &3Mount & Dismount&n
#
BRIEF

&2Brief&n

&3Usage:&n &4brief&n

Toggles "brief mode".  When in brief mode, you don't see the descriptions of
the room you are in; only the name of the room and the people and objects
there.  Unless you're very familiar with the area in which you're traveling,
however, it is not advisable to use this command.  Frequently, you will find
small but vital hints in the descriptions of the rooms: An extra peek at your
surroundings could mean the difference between life and death!

If you explicitly type 'look', you will always see the full room description,
even in BRIEF mode.

See also: &3Compact, Look&n
#
BUG TYPO IDEA TODO

&2Bug Typo Idea Todo&n

&3Usage: &4[bug | idea | typo | todo] <option>&n

&3    options:&n 
&3    	add 
	edit <number> 
	delete <number>
	list ['self' | <state> | <player>]
	print <number>

&3add&n: 	creates a new report
&3edit&n:	edits the given report
&3delete&n:	deletes the given report
&3list&n:	lists existing reports, 
		optionally filtered by ['self' | <state> | <&7player&n>]
  'self': 	lists only the reports that you are responsible for.
  <state>:	lists reports only of the given state 
  		(OPEN, ASSESSED, FEEDBACK, CLOSED)
  <player>:	lists only the reports that <player> is responsible for
&3print&n:	displays the full details of the given report	

For full information about &RPrimalMUD's&n reporting system type &4help reporting&n.

See also: &3REPORTING, LISTREPORTS, PRINTREPORT&n
#
"REPORTING SYSTEM"

&2Reporting System&n

&RPrimalMUD&n version 3 saw the implementation of a new reporting system.
This report management system allows players to use a menu based system to 
add information about the &4bug&n/&4typo&n/&4idea&n/&4todo&n report. It is designed to provide
better communication over the tradition &4bug&n/&4typo&n/&4idea&n commands which logs
the text directly to file which usually ends up being ignored.

&3Lifecycle&n
&3---------&n
Initially when a report is created, the state is set to &3OPEN&n. When the
responsible person looks at the report, they should edit it and change the
state to &3ASSESSED&n (so the reporter knows the report has been looked at).
The responsible person should then fix/respond to the problem and change
the state to &3FEEDBACK&n. The reporter then verifies the fix/responce and
edits the report changing the state to &3CLOSED&n. Obvious exceptions apply to
a more complicated report, but the state principals as mentioned above
should be used consistantly as described.

Reports which have the &3DELETED&n state are still kept in file, but are not
visible from within the game.

&3Notification&n
&3------------&n
Every time that a report is modified, notification is given to the involved
parties (all people that have made a change to the initial report). This
notification is in the form of mudmail and includes the change description
as well information on how to view the entire details.

&3Restrictions&n
&3------------&n
Various restrictions have been put into the reporting system to ensure that
the system runs smoothly and as intended (holds appropiate privacy).

There are some restrictions that apply when using the report editor, but the
main restriction that apply on report usage are as follows:

Command      	list/print                      edit/delete
-------		----------			-----------
&3BUG&n          	<  GOD - owned reports          <  GRGOD - owned reports
		>= GOD - all reports            >= GRGOD - all reports

&3IDEA&n         	<  ANGEL - owned reports        <  GRGOD - owned reports
		>= ANGEL - all reports          >= GRGOD - all reports

&3TYPO&n         	<  IMMORT - owned reports       <  GOD - owned reports
              	>= IMMORT - all reports         >= GOD - all reports

&3TODO&n         	<  ANGEL - owned reports        <  GRGOD - owned reports
		>= ANGEL - all reports          >= GRGOD - all reports


See also: &3BUG IDEA TODO TYPO LISTREPORTS PRINTREPORT&n
#
BUY

&2Buy&n

&3Usage:&n &4buy <item name>
       buy #<item number>
       buy n.<item name>
       buy n <item name>
       buy n #<item number>&n

If you'd like to purchase an item from a shop and have the money, you can buy
it.  Items can be bought by name, or by their number in the shop listing,
and can be bought in quantity.
 
Examples:
 
  > buy sword        (buy the first sword on the list)
  > buy #3           (buy the third item on the list)
  > buy 4.sword      (buy the fourth sword on the list)
  > buy 10 bread     (buy 10 pieces of bread)
  > buy 10 #2        (buy 10 of the second item on the list)
 
See also: &3LIST, SELL, SHOPS, VALUE&n
#
CAST

&2Cast&n

Used by Magic Users and Clerics (and the occasional other character) for
the casting of spells.

&3Usage:&n &4cast <'spell'> <player>&n

   Note that the name of the spell must be enclosed by the holy symbols "&3'&n".

See also: help on each individual spell, for example:
  > help fireball
  > help call lightning
  > help energy drain
#
CLEAR CLS

&2Clear Cls&n

Clears the text on the screen. 
Handy for those moments when someone walks in and you have a screen full of ....
#
