AFFECTS

&2Affects&n

&3Usage:&n &4affects&n

An affect is something that modifies your attributes.
These are usually made active on you by casting spells or using skills.

This command displays all of your current affects, at level 20 the
amount of information displayed is increased.
#
ALIAS ALIASES

&2Alias or Aliases&n

&3Usage:&n &4alias [<alias name>] [command]&n

An alias is a single command used to represent one or more other commands.
The &4ALIAS&n command can be used to manipulate your character's aliases.  Type
&4ALIAS&n alone to see a list of your currently defined aliases.
The &3<alias name>&n must be one word.  The &3command&n can be any string.  
Aliases may not be nested or used recursively.  Any command may be overridden 
by an alias (other than the &4ALIAS&n command itself, of course).

  > &4alias gbb get bread bag&n
  > &4alias gac get all corpse&n

Type &4alias <alias-name>&n to delete an alias that has already been defined.

  > &4alias gbb&n

A semicolon (";") can be used to define multiple actions to be taken with
a single alias. 
(Note a semicolon may be interpreted differently as "input" in some clients)

  > &4alias eat get bread bag; eat bread&n

Note that the 'eat' contained within the eat alias is interpreted as the MUD's
internal eat command; aliases may not be nested or used recursively.  The
variables &3$1, $2, ... $9&n may be used to represent arguments given with
an alias.

Examples:

  > &4alias killem cast 'fireball' $1; cast 'harm' $2&n
  > &4killem fido mage&n

Would cast fireball on fido, followed by casting harm on mage.  Variables
may be used repeatedly and in any order:

  > &4alias helpem cast 'heal' $1; cast 'bless' $1; cast 'armor' $1&n

The special variable &3$*&n represents the entire input line after an alias:

  > &4alias tr tell rasmussen $*&n
  > &4tr hi there, how are you today?&n
  &rYou tell &7Rasmussen&r, 'hi there, how are you today?'&n

See also: &3! ^&n
#
ANSI COLOUR COLOR
&2"Ansi Colour"&n

&3Usage:&n &4colour [off | sparse | normal | complete]&n

If you have a colour-capable terminal and wish to see useful colour-coding
of information, use the &4colour&n command to set the level of colouring you see.
These four subcommands turn colour on && off to various levels.  Experiment to see
which level suits your personal taste.

'&4colour&n' with no argument will display your current colour level.

Using colour will slow down the speed at which you see messages VERY slightly.
The effect is more noticeable on slower connections.  Even if you have
colour turned on, non-colourised messages will not be slowed down at all.

&RPrimalMUD&n implements &rEasy Colour v2.2&n, which interprets inline colour codes.
Colours can be displayed in your text by inserting a &3&&&n followed by a &3<char code>&n.

The &3<char codes>&n correspond to the following colours:
&rr	Red&n 		&gg	Green&n 	
&yy	Yellow&n		&bb	Blue&n
&mm	Magenta&n 	&cc	Cyan&n
&ww	White&n
&RR	Bold Red&n 	&GG	Bold Green&n
&YY	Bold Yellow&n 	&BB	Bold Blue&n
&MM	Bold Magenta&n 	&CC	Bold Cyan&n
&WW	Bold White&n

Additionally, there are a number of special codes including:
&nn	Normal&n	
&vv	Reverse&n	
&uu	Underline&n
[	Set mark&n	]	Colour of set mark&n

example:
  > &4gossip &&[I am feeling a bit &&GSICK&&] today!&n
            ^ 			       ^    	
          colour                   changes
	 here is  		  to colour
	  yellow  	      at last mark (&&[ = yellow)
              \/                      \/
  &yYou gossip, 'I am feeling a bit &[&GSICK&] today!'

See also: &3COLOURSET&n
#
